UR  - https://www.sciencedirect.com/science/article/pii/0304387881900122
AB  - The hypothesis that inflation is not neutral with respect to relative commodity prices has recently received a great deal of attention. In this paper the recent experience of Argentina, a country suffering from a very high rate of inflation, is considered. It is found that the increase in relative-price variability which is associated with higher rates of inflation is caused mainly by ‘surprises’ or unanticipated changes in the inflation rate and that fully expected inflation appears to have less or no relative-price effects. An additional result indicates that increased variability of relative commodity prices have effects on financial portfolio composition, reducing the holdings of real cash balances.
