AB  - The possibility of gradual transition to collective agriculture on the basis of peasant self-interest is examined theoretically and with reference to the Tanzanian experience. After discussing relevant aspects of Tanzania's recent agricultural history and development policies, the author summarizes the findings of a theoretical investigation of individual and collective choice in two-sector, democratic villages. The result of research conducted in several Tanzanian villages to test the theoretical framework and investigate the principal factors influencing adoption of collective production are then reported and evaluated.
